      "title": "See also"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The Hamming window is defined as"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "formulas": [
            "w(n) = 0.54 - 0.46\\cos\\left(\\frac{2\\pi{n}}{M-1}\\right) \\qquad 0 \\leq n \\leq M-1"
          ],
          "type": "math_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The Hamming was named for R. W. Hamming, an associate of J. W. Tukey\nand is described in Blackman and Tukey. It was recommended for\nsmoothing the truncated autocovariance function in the time domain.\nMost references to the Hamming window come from the signal processing\nliterature, where it is used as one of many windowing functions for\nsmoothing values.  It is also known as an apodization (which means\n\"removing the foot\", i.e. smoothing discontinuities at the beginning\nand end of the sampled signal) or tapering function."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Notes"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "1\n\nBlackman, R.B. and Tukey, J.W., (1958) The measurement of power\nspectra, Dover Publications, New York.",
          "type": "raw_block"
        },
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "2\n\nE.R. Kanasewich, \"Time Sequence Analysis in Geophysics\", The\nUniversity of Alberta Press, 1975, pp. 109-110.",
          "type": "raw_block"
        },
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "3\n\nWikipedia, \"Window function\",\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Window_function",
          "type": "raw_block"
        },
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "4\n\nW.H. Press,  B.P. Flannery, S.A. Teukolsky, and W.T. Vetterling,\n\"Numerical Recipes\", Cambridge University Press, 1986, page 425.",
          "type": "raw_block"
        }
      ],
      "title": "References"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "import flopscope as fnp"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "fnp.hamming(12)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([ 0.08      ,  0.15302337,  0.34890909,  0.60546483,  0.84123594, # may vary"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "        0.98136677,  0.98136677,  0.84123594,  0.60546483,  0.34890909,"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "        0.15302337,  0.08      ])"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Plot the window and the frequency response."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "argument_inline": [],
          "content_blocks": [
            {
              "language": "python",
              "text": "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nfrom fnp.fft import fft, fftshift\nwindow = fnp.hamming(51)\nplt.plot(window)\nplt.title(\"Hamming window\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Amplitude\")\nplt.xlabel(\"Sample\")\nplt.show()\n\nplt.figure()\nA = fft(window, 2048) / 25.5\nmag = fnp.abs(fftshift(A))\nfreq = fnp.linspace(-0.5, 0.5, len(A))\nresponse = 20 * fnp.log10(mag)\nresponse = fnp.clip(response, -100, 100)\nplt.plot(freq, response)\nplt.title(\"Frequency response of Hamming window\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Magnitude [dB]\")\nplt.xlabel(\"Normalized frequency [cycles per sample]\")\nplt.axis('tight')\nplt.show()",
              "type": "literal_block"
            }
          ],
          "directive": "plot",
          "options": [
            {
              "name": "include-source",
              "value": ""
            }
          ],
          "raw_source": ".. plot::\n    :include-source:\n\n    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n    from numpy.fft import fft, fftshift\n    window = np.hamming(51)\n    plt.plot(window)\n    plt.title(\"Hamming window\")\n    plt.ylabel(\"Amplitude\")\n    plt.xlabel(\"Sample\")\n    plt.show()\n\n    plt.figure()\n    A = fft(window, 2048) / 25.5\n    mag = np.abs(fftshift(A))\n    freq = np.linspace(-0.5, 0.5, len(A))\n    response = 20 * np.log10(mag)\n    response = np.clip(response, -100, 100)\n    plt.plot(freq, response)\n    plt.title(\"Frequency response of Hamming window\")\n    plt.ylabel(\"Magnitude [dB]\")\n    plt.xlabel(\"Normalized frequency [cycles per sample]\")\n    plt.axis('tight')\n    plt.show()",
          "supported": true,
          "type": "directive_block"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Examples"
    }
